<br>
2 things...<br>
<br>
1. There is more then one reason why the USA dropped the bomb. There is the the very PR, but in my oppinion honest, reason you mentioned. To save lives which would be lost in a conventional invasion. The second, but equally important thing, is that Stalin was moving his forces in to help finish off the Japanese. If any russians would have been killed in the ensuing invasion, he would undoubtedly want a share of the spoils of war afterwards. In other words, the bomb was dropped to end the war before Russia got into it, because the little children didn't want to share. This show that the US's motives were not entirely so humanitarian. Ultimately though, I think the reasons for dropping them were political. Truman could not face american people, and tell them sacrificing 500,000 american lives in an invasion were nessesary, while holding an weapon like the bomb in his hands. Most importantly, if this had happened, and people found out later about the bomb later, they would never reelect him. <br>
<br>
2. Its true that the atomic bomb was dropped during a time of war, on an enemy nation. But remember that the 89,000 killed in Hiroshima were almost all civilians. At the time the US population (who were so anti-Japanese that they wouldnt have cared anyway) were told that Hiroshima was a military target. The only reason the US Government could get away with this lie is because Hiroshima had a few factories and a small garrison. What they forgot to mention is that every city in Japan had a garrison... they were after all, at war and ready to defend each city. Its like saying my house is a military target because my neighbor happenes to be in the reserves. <br>
<br>
To make my point, that the hiroshima bomb was in fact targeted at civilians, makes it not completely unlike the recent terrorist attack. I agree with you that its not a direct analogy, and there for I wouldn't use it. But while its definately politicly incorrect, its not entirely incorrect. <br>
<br>
